<div class="kriskogram">
	<p>
		Traditional flow maps struggle to convey human migration patterns due to visual clutter and spatial layout constraints. Kriskograms address these limitations through an abstract representation: nodes arranged along a horizontal axis with migration flows as semicircular arcs. This project implements an interactive kriskogram application with two novel interaction features: <strong>Ego Focus</strong> (k-neighbor filtering centered on a single node for pattern recognition) and <strong>Temporal Overlay</strong> (multiple time periods rendered simultaneously in static or animated mode). The animated mode segments arcs and maps segment speed to flow weight, enabling direct comparison of flow magnitudes through motion.
	</p>
	<p>
		Built with React, Vite, D3.js, IndexedDB, and TanStack Router. Uses U.S. Census state-to-state migration data (2005-2019). Done for <a href="https://vis.uib.no/courses/inf358/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">INF358 Seminar in Visualization</a> at the University of Bergen.
	</p>
